{"title_page": "Kostas Antetokounmpo", "text_new": "{{short description|Greek basketball player}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2019}}\n{{Infobox basketball biography\n| name = Kostas Antetokounmpo\n| image = \n| image_size = \n| caption = \n| league = [[NBA]]\n| team = Los Angeles Lakers\n| number = 37\n| position = [[Power forward (basketball)|Power forward]]\n| height_ft = 6\n| height_in = 10\n| weight_lbs = 220\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1997|11|20}}\n| birth_place = [[Athens]], Greece\n| nationality = Greek\n| high_school = [[Dominican High School (Whitefish Bay, Wisconsin)|Dominican]]<br>([[Whitefish Bay, Wisconsin]])\n| college = [[Dayton Flyers men's basketball|Dayton]] (2017\u20132018)\n| draft_year = 2018\n| draft_round = 2\n| draft_pick = 60\n| draft_team = [[Philadelphia 76ers]]\n| career_start = 2018\n| career_end = \n| years1 = {{nbay|2018|full=y}}\n| team1 = [[Dallas Mavericks]]\n| years2 = 2018\u20132019\n| team2 = \u2192[[Texas Legends]]\n| years3 = {{nbay|2019|start}}\u2013present\n| team3 = [[Los Angeles Lakers]]\n| years4 = 2019\u2013present\n| team4 = \u2192[[South Bay Lakers]]\n| profile = kostas_antetokounmpo\n| bbr = antetko01\n}}\n'''Kostas Ndubuisi Antetokounmpo''' ({{respell|AHN|teh|tuh|KOOM|poh|}}; {{lang-el|\u039a\u03ce\u03c3\u03c4\u03b1\u03c2 \u0391\u03bd\u03c4\u03b5\u03c4\u03bf\u03ba\u03bf\u03cd\u03bd\u03bc\u03c0\u03bf}}) (born November 20, 1997)<ref>[http://archive.fiba.com/pages/eng/fa/player/p/pid/126901/sid/12474/tid/291/_/2016_FIBA_U20_European_Championship_Division_B/index.html Ndubuisi Antetokounmpo DOB: 20 Nov.1997 Place of birth: Athens (GRE).]</ref> is a Greek professional [[basketball]] player for the [[Los Angeles Lakers]] of the [[National Basketball Association]] (NBA), on a [[two-way contract]] with the [[South Bay Lakers]] of the [[NBA G League]]. He was drafted 60th overall by the [[Philadelphia 76ers]] in the [[2018 NBA draft]], and his draft rights were then traded to the Dallas Mavericks.<ref name=\"realgm\">{{cite web|title=Kostas Antetokounmpo|url=https://basketball.realgm.com/player/Kostas-Antetokounmpo/Summary/93018|publisher=[[RealGM]]|accessdate=March 22, 2018}}</ref> He attended and played [[college basketball|collegiate level basketball]] in the United States for the [[Dayton Flyers men's basketball|Dayton Flyers]]. Two of his older brothers, [[Giannis Antetokounmpo|Giannis]] and [[Thanasis Antetokounmpo|Thanasis]], both play for the [[Milwaukee Bucks]] of the [[National Basketball Association]] (NBA).<ref>{{cite web |title=Lakers claim Giannis' younger brother, Kostas |url=https://www.espn.com/nba/story/_/id/27239420/lakers-claim-giannis-younger-brother-kostas |website=ESPN.com |accessdate=February 17, 2020 |date=September 11, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Early years==\nAntetokounmpo was born in [[Sepolia]] in [[Athens, Greece]]. As a youth, he began playing the sport of basketball with the junior youth teams of [[Filathlitikos BC|Filathlitikos]], in Athens.\n\n==High school career==\nAfter his older brother [[Giannis Antetokounmpo|Giannis]] was drafted by the [[Milwaukee Bucks]] in the [[2013 NBA draft]], Antetokounmpo, along with his parents and his younger brother, Alexis, moved to Milwaukee. He attended [[Dominican High School (Whitefish Bay, Wisconsin)|Dominican High School]] in [[Whitefish Bay, Wisconsin]],<ref name=\"dominican\">{{cite web|last1=Stewart|first1=Mark|title=Kostas Antetokounmpo making a name for himself at Dominican|url=http://archive.jsonline.com/sports/preps/kostas-antetokounmpo-making-a-name-for-himself-at-dominican-b99670083z1-368913091.html/|website=[[Milwaukee Journal Sentinel]]|accessdate=March 22, 2018|date=February 15, 2016}}</ref> where he played high school basketball during his junior and senior years. As a senior, he led his team to a state championship.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://daytonflyers.com/roster.aspx?rp_id=4218|title=Kostas Antetokounmpo \u2013 2016\u201317|access-date=May 31, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==College career==\nAfter high school, Antetokounmpo moved on to play [[college basketball]] at the [[University of Dayton]]. In the [[2016\u201317 Dayton Flyers men's basketball team|2016\u201317 season]], his first with the [[Dayton Flyers men's basketball|Flyers]], he was [[redshirt (college sports)|red-shirted]],<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.midmajormadness.com/2016/10/3/13148932/dayton-flyers-kostas-antetokounmpo-ineligible-redshirt-ncaa|title=Dayton's Kostas Antetokounmpo ruled ineligible for 2016\u201317|work=Mid-Major Madness|access-date=May 31, 2018}}</ref> after being ruled a \"partial qualifier\",<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://collegebasketball.nbcsports.com/2016/10/03/kostas-antetokounmpo-ruled-ineligible-for-dayton/|title=Kostas Antetokounmpo ruled ineligible for Dayton|date=October 3, 2016|work=CollegeBasketballTalk|access-date=May 31, 2018}}</ref> due to having spent his first two years of high school in Greece.<ref>[https://flyerfaithful.com/kostas-antetokounmpo-may-have-to-sit-the-2016-17-season-out-88140697b419 Kostas Antetokounmpo may have to sit the 2016\u201317 season out.]{{Dead link|date=February 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> He debuted in the [[2017\u201318 Dayton Flyers men's basketball team|2017\u201318 season]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cbb/players/kostas-antetokounmpo-1.html|title=Kostas Antetokounmpo College Stats {{!}} College Basketball at Sports-Reference.com|website=College Basketball at Sports-Reference.com|access-date=May 31, 2018}}</ref> averaging 5.2 points, 2.9 rebounds, 0.4 assists, 0.2 steals, and 1.1 blocks per game, in 15.1 minutes per game.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/mens-college-basketball/player/_/id/4066490/kostas-antetokounmpo|title=Kostas Antetokounmpo|publisher=ESPN|access-date=May 31, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Professional career==\n===Dallas Mavericks / Texas Legends (2018\u20132019)===\nOn March 22, 2018, Antetokounmpo declared for the [[2018 NBA draft]].<ref name=\"draft\">{{cite web|last1=Givony|first1=Jonathan|title=Kostas Antetokounmpo to test NBA draft waters|url=http://www.espn.com/nba/story/_/id/22873095/kostas-antetokounmpo-dayton-flyers-enter-nba-draft-test-waters|publisher=[[ESPN]]|accessdate=March 22, 2018|date=March 22, 2018}}</ref> On May 4, 2018, Antetokounmpo would be one of a record-high 69 players to enter the [[NBA Draft Combine]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://sports.yahoo.com/complete-2018-nba-draft-combine-list-211843026.html|title=Some of college basketball's biggest names highlight NBA draft combine list|access-date=May 31, 2018}}</ref> Antetokounmpo was projected to be a second round selection, similar to his older brother [[Thanasis Antetokounmpo|Thanasis]], due to his lack of notable progress in his redshirt freshman college season. He would ultimately wind up being the last pick of the [[2018 NBA draft]], after being selected by the [[Philadelphia 76ers]], only to then be immediately traded to the [[Dallas Mavericks]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.daytondailynews.com/sports/dayton-draft-drought-ends-antetokounmpo-chosen-with-last-pick/LWtNcq9ztfmGFeZQZ9tS9L/|title=Dayton draft drought ends as Antetokounmpo chosen with last pick|newspaper=[[Dayton Daily News]]|date=June 21, 2018|accessdate=June 22, 2018|first=David|last=Jablonski}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mavs.com/mavericks-acquire-draft-rights-to-ray-spalding-and-kostas-antetokounmpo/|title=Mavericks acquire draft rights to Ray Spalding and Kostas Antetokounmpo|date=June 21, 2018|access-date=June 21, 2018|publisher=mavs.com}}</ref> Antetokounmpo would later sign a [[two-way contract]] on July 13. Throughout the contract, he will split his playing time between the Mavericks and their [[NBA G League]] affiliate, the [[Texas Legends]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Mavericks sign Kostas Antetokounmpo to two-way contract; waive Jalen Jones|url=https://www.mavs.com/mavericks-sign-kostas-antetokounmpo-to-two-way-contract-waive-jalen-jones/|publisher=National Basketball Association|date=July 13, 2018|accessdate=July 13, 2018}}</ref> He made his NBA debut on March 20, 2019 in a 118\u2013126 loss to the [[Portland Trail Blazers]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Lillard scores 33 points, Blazers beat Mavericks 126\u2013118|url=http://www.espn.com/nba/recap?gameId=401071746|publisher=National Basketball Association|date=March 20, 2019|accessdate=March 20, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Los Angeles Lakers / South Bay Lakers (2019\u2013present)===\nOn July 19, 2019, Antetokounmpo was waived by the Mavericks.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mavsmoneyball.com/2019/7/19/20701354/dallas-mavericks-waive-kostas-antetokounmpo=21|title=Mavericks waive Kostas Antetokounmpo|date=July 19, 2019|website=mavsmoneyball.com|access-date=July 19, 2019}}</ref> He would later be claimed by the [[Los Angeles Lakers]] on July 22, 2019.<ref>{{cite web |title=Report: Lakers claim Kostas Antetokounmpo off free agency waivers |url=https://www.nba.com/article/2019/07/21/report-lakers-claim-kostas-antetokounmpo-waivers |website=NBA |accessdate=22 July 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Lakers Awarded Kostas Antetokounmpo on Waiver Claim |url=https://www.nba.com/lakers/releases/190722-lakers-awarded-kostas-antetokounmpo-waiver-claim |website=Los Angeles Lakers |accessdate=22 July 2019}}</ref>\n\n==National team career==\nAntetokounmpo played with the junior [[Greece men's national under-20 basketball team|Greek Under-20 national team]]. He played at the [[2016 FIBA Europe Under-20 Championship Division B]], where he won a bronze medal.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://archive.fiba.com/pages/eng/fa/p/rpp//q/Ndubuisi%20ADETOKUNBO/pid/126901/_//players.html|title=archive.fiba.com: Players|website=archive.fiba.com|access-date=May 31, 2018}}</ref> During the tournament, he averaged 1.3 points, 1.8 rebounds, and 0.3 assists per game.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://archive.fiba.com/pages/eng/fa/player/p/pid/126901/sid/12474/tid/291/_/2016_FIBA_U20_European_Championship_Division_B/index.html|title=Ndubuisi Antetokounmpo profile, FIBA U20 European Championship 2016 {{!}} FIBA.COM|work=FIBA.COM|access-date=May 31, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Career statistics==\n{{NBA player statistics legend}}\n\n===NBA===\n====Regular season====\n{{NBA player statistics start}}\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| {{nbay|2018}}\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| [[2018\u201319 Dallas Mavericks season|Dallas]]\n| 2 || 0 || 5.5 || .000 || .000 || .500 || .5 || .0 || 1.0 || .0 || 1.0\n|- class=\"sortbottom\"\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" colspan=\"2\"| Career\n| 2 || 0 || 5.5 || .000 || .000 || .500 || .5 || .0 || 1.0 || .0 || 1.0\n{{S-end}}\n\n===College===\n{{NBA player statistics start}}\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| [[2017\u201318 NCAA Division I men's basketball season|2017\u201318]]\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| [[2017\u201318 Dayton Flyers men's basketball team|Dayton]]\n| 29 || 6 || 21.1 || .574 || .133 || .516 || 2.9 || .4 || .2 || 1.1 || 5.2\n{{S-end}}\n\n==Personal life==\nAntetokounmpo was born in [[Athens]], Greece, to [[Nigerians|Nigerian]] parents. He officially became a full Greek citizen in 2016.<ref>[http://www.matrix24.gr/2016/01/vgazi-elliniko-diavatirio-o-kostas-antetokounmpo/ matrix24.gr \u0392\u03b3\u03ac\u03b6\u03b5\u03b9 \u03b5\u03bb\u03bb\u03b7\u03bd\u03b9\u03ba\u03cc \u03b4\u03b9\u03b1\u03b2\u03b1\u03c4\u03ae\u03c1\u03b9\u03bf \u03bf \u039a\u03ce\u03c3\u03c4\u03b1\u03c2 \u0391\u03bd\u03c4\u03b5\u03c4\u03bf\u03ba\u03bf\u03cd\u03bd\u03bc\u03c0\u03bf {{in lang|el}}.]</ref> In addition, along with his younger sibling, Alexis, he has a Nigerian passport, which was granted to him in June 2013, so that he could gain a [[visa policy of the United States|visa]], and be allowed to legally enter into the United States.<ref>[http://www.gazzetta.gr/basketball/article/916698/i-halasmeni-kafetiera gazzetta.gr \u0397 \u03c7\u03b1\u03bb\u03b1\u03c3\u03bc\u03ad\u03bd\u03b7 \u03ba\u03b1\u03c6\u03b5\u03c4\u03b9\u03ad\u03c1\u03b1  {{in lang|el}}.]</ref>\n\nHis late father, Charles, was a former Nigerian [[association football|soccer]] player, while his mother, Veronica, was a [[high jumper]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.npr.org/2013/09/26/226268651/nbas-g-bo-wants-to-bring-hope-to-greece-and-to-milwaukee|title=NBA Rookie Wants To Bring Hope To Greece, And To Milwaukee|publisher=NPR|access-date=May 31, 2018}}</ref> Charles died in September 2017, at age 54.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/nba/recap?gameId=400974785|title=Trail Blazers vs. Bucks \u2013 Game Recap \u2013 October 21, 2017|publisher=ESPN|access-date=May 31, 2018}}</ref> His parents are from different Nigerian ethnic groups\u2014Charles was [[Yoruba people|Yoruba]], and Veronica is [[Igbo people|Igbo]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://theundefeated.com/features/bucks-giannis-antetokounmpo-greek-freak-wants-to-go-back-to-his-nigerian-roots/ |title=\u2018The Greek Freak\u2019 wants to go back to his Nigerian roots |first=Marc J. |last=Spears |publisher=[[The Undefeated (website)|The Undefeated]] |date=March 5, 2019 |accessdate=March 8, 2019}}</ref> His oldest brother, Francis, is also a professional soccer player. He is a younger brother of [[Milwaukee Bucks]] players [[Giannis Antetokounmpo|Giannis]] and [[Thanasis Antetokounmpo|Thanasis]]. He is also the older brother of Alex.<ref name=\"archdeacon\">{{cite web|last1=Archdeacon|first1=Tom|title=Flyers\u2019 Kostas Antetokounmpo tries to live up to his name|url=https://www.mydaytondailynews.com/sports/tom-archdeacon-flyers-kostas-antetokounmpo-tries-live-his-name/meHZJCKf9vQXNYVhHne5gL/|website=[[Dayton Daily News]]|accessdate=March 22, 2018|date=September 23, 2017}}</ref> As a youth, Antetokounmpo played for the junior clubs of [[Filathlitikos B.C.|Filathlitikos]], which also developed his older brothers Thanasis and Giannis.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.proballers.com/basketball/player/66983/konstantinos-antetokounmpo Proballers.com Profile]\n*[http://www.nba.com/players/kostas/antetokounmpo/1628961 NBA.com profile]\n*[http://daytonflyers.com/roster.aspx?rp_id=4218&path= Dayton Flyers bio]\n\n{{Los Angeles Lakers current roster}}\n{{South Bay Lakers current roster}}\n{{2018 NBA Draft}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Antetokounmpo, Kostas}}\n[[Category:1997 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Dallas Mavericks players]]\n[[Category:Dayton Flyers men's basketball players]]\n[[Category:Nigerian emigrants to the United States]]\n[[Category:Greek expatriate basketball people in the United States]]\n[[Category:Greek men's basketball players]]\n[[Category:Greek people of Nigerian descent]]\n[[Category:Greek people of Igbo descent]]\n[[Category:Greek people of Yoruba descent]]\n[[Category:Igbo sportspeople]]\n[[Category:Los Angeles Lakers players]]\n[[Category:Philadelphia 76ers draft picks]]\n[[Category:Power forwards (basketball)]]\n[[Category:South Bay Lakers players]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Athens]]\n[[Category:Texas Legends players]]\n[[Category:Yoruba sportspeople]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Greek basketball player}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2019}}\n{{Infobox basketball biography\n| name = Kostas Antetokounmpo\n| image = \n| image_size = \n| caption = \n| league = [[NBA]]\n| team = Los Angeles Lakers\n| number = 37\n| position = [[Power forward (basketball)|Power forward]]\n| height_ft = 6\n| height_in = 10\n| weight_lbs = 220\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1997|11|20}}\n| birth_place = [[Athens]], Greece\n| nationality = Greek\n| high_school = [[Dominican High School (Whitefish Bay, Wisconsin)|Dominican]]<br>([[Whitefish Bay, Wisconsin]])\n| college = [[Dayton Flyers men's basketball|Dayton]] (2017\u20132018)\n| draft_year = 2018\n| draft_round = 2\n| draft_pick = 60\n| draft_team = [[Philadelphia 76ers]]\n| career_start = 2018\n| career_end = \n| years1 = {{nbay|2018|full=y}}\n| team1 = [[Dallas Mavericks]]\n| years2 = 2018\u20132019\n| team2 = \u2192[[Texas Legends]]\n| years3 = {{nbay|2019|start}}\u2013present\n| team3 = [[Los Angeles Lakers]]\n| years4 = 2019\u2013present\n| team4 = \u2192[[South Bay Lakers]]\n| profile = kostas_antetokounmpo\n| bbr = antetko01\n}}\n'''Kostas Ndubuisi Antetokounmpo''' ({{lang-el|\u039a\u03ce\u03c3\u03c4\u03b1\u03c2 \u0391\u03bd\u03c4\u03b5\u03c4\u03bf\u03ba\u03bf\u03cd\u03bd\u03bc\u03c0\u03bf}}) (born November 20, 1997)<ref>[http://archive.fiba.com/pages/eng/fa/player/p/pid/126901/sid/12474/tid/291/_/2016_FIBA_U20_European_Championship_Division_B/index.html Ndubuisi Antetokounmpo DOB: 20 Nov.1997 Place of birth: Athens (GRE).]</ref> is a Greek professional [[basketball]] player for the [[Los Angeles Lakers]] of the [[National Basketball Association]] (NBA), on a [[two-way contract]] with the [[South Bay Lakers]] of the [[NBA G League]]. He was drafted 60th overall by the [[Philadelphia 76ers]] in the [[2018 NBA draft]], and his draft rights were then traded to the Dallas Mavericks.<ref name=\"realgm\">{{cite web|title=Kostas Antetokounmpo|url=https://basketball.realgm.com/player/Kostas-Antetokounmpo/Summary/93018|publisher=[[RealGM]]|accessdate=March 22, 2018}}</ref> He attended and played [[college basketball|collegiate level basketball]] in the United States for the [[Dayton Flyers men's basketball|Dayton Flyers]]. Two of his older brothers, [[Giannis Antetokounmpo|Giannis]] and [[Thanasis Antetokounmpo|Thanasis]], both play for the [[Milwaukee Bucks]] of the [[National Basketball Association]] (NBA).<ref>{{cite web |title=Lakers claim Giannis' younger brother, Kostas |url=https://www.espn.com/nba/story/_/id/27239420/lakers-claim-giannis-younger-brother-kostas |website=ESPN.com |accessdate=February 17, 2020 |date=September 11, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Early years==\nAntetokounmpo was born in [[Sepolia]] in [[Athens, Greece]]. As a youth, he began playing the sport of basketball with the junior youth teams of [[Filathlitikos BC|Filathlitikos]], in Athens.\n\n==High school career==\nAfter his older brother [[Giannis Antetokounmpo|Giannis]] was drafted by the [[Milwaukee Bucks]] in the [[2013 NBA draft]], Antetokounmpo, along with his parents and his younger brother, Alexis, moved to Milwaukee. He attended [[Dominican High School (Whitefish Bay, Wisconsin)|Dominican High School]] in [[Whitefish Bay, Wisconsin]],<ref name=\"dominican\">{{cite web|last1=Stewart|first1=Mark|title=Kostas Antetokounmpo making a name for himself at Dominican|url=http://archive.jsonline.com/sports/preps/kostas-antetokounmpo-making-a-name-for-himself-at-dominican-b99670083z1-368913091.html/|website=[[Milwaukee Journal Sentinel]]|accessdate=March 22, 2018|date=February 15, 2016}}</ref> where he played high school basketball during his junior and senior years. As a senior, he led his team to a state championship.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://daytonflyers.com/roster.aspx?rp_id=4218|title=Kostas Antetokounmpo \u2013 2016\u201317|access-date=May 31, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==College career==\nAfter high school, Antetokounmpo moved on to play [[college basketball]] at the [[University of Dayton]]. In the [[2016\u201317 Dayton Flyers men's basketball team|2016\u201317 season]], his first with the [[Dayton Flyers men's basketball|Flyers]], he was [[redshirt (college sports)|red-shirted]],<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.midmajormadness.com/2016/10/3/13148932/dayton-flyers-kostas-antetokounmpo-ineligible-redshirt-ncaa|title=Dayton's Kostas Antetokounmpo ruled ineligible for 2016\u201317|work=Mid-Major Madness|access-date=May 31, 2018}}</ref> after being ruled a \"partial qualifier\",<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://collegebasketball.nbcsports.com/2016/10/03/kostas-antetokounmpo-ruled-ineligible-for-dayton/|title=Kostas Antetokounmpo ruled ineligible for Dayton|date=October 3, 2016|work=CollegeBasketballTalk|access-date=May 31, 2018}}</ref> due to having spent his first two years of high school in Greece.<ref>[https://flyerfaithful.com/kostas-antetokounmpo-may-have-to-sit-the-2016-17-season-out-88140697b419 Kostas Antetokounmpo may have to sit the 2016\u201317 season out.]{{Dead link|date=February 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> He debuted in the [[2017\u201318 Dayton Flyers men's basketball team|2017\u201318 season]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cbb/players/kostas-antetokounmpo-1.html|title=Kostas Antetokounmpo College Stats {{!}} College Basketball at Sports-Reference.com|website=College Basketball at Sports-Reference.com|access-date=May 31, 2018}}</ref> averaging 5.2 points, 2.9 rebounds, 0.4 assists, 0.2 steals, and 1.1 blocks per game, in 15.1 minutes per game.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/mens-college-basketball/player/_/id/4066490/kostas-antetokounmpo|title=Kostas Antetokounmpo|publisher=ESPN|access-date=May 31, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Professional career==\n===Dallas Mavericks / Texas Legends (2018\u20132019)===\nOn March 22, 2018, Antetokounmpo declared for the [[2018 NBA draft]].<ref name=\"draft\">{{cite web|last1=Givony|first1=Jonathan|title=Kostas Antetokounmpo to test NBA draft waters|url=http://www.espn.com/nba/story/_/id/22873095/kostas-antetokounmpo-dayton-flyers-enter-nba-draft-test-waters|publisher=[[ESPN]]|accessdate=March 22, 2018|date=March 22, 2018}}</ref> On May 4, 2018, Antetokounmpo would be one of a record-high 69 players to enter the [[NBA Draft Combine]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://sports.yahoo.com/complete-2018-nba-draft-combine-list-211843026.html|title=Some of college basketball's biggest names highlight NBA draft combine list|access-date=May 31, 2018}}</ref> Antetokounmpo was projected to be a second round selection, similar to his older brother [[Thanasis Antetokounmpo|Thanasis]], due to his lack of notable progress in his redshirt freshman college season. He would ultimately wind up being the last pick of the [[2018 NBA draft]], after being selected by the [[Philadelphia 76ers]], only to then be immediately traded to the [[Dallas Mavericks]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.daytondailynews.com/sports/dayton-draft-drought-ends-antetokounmpo-chosen-with-last-pick/LWtNcq9ztfmGFeZQZ9tS9L/|title=Dayton draft drought ends as Antetokounmpo chosen with last pick|newspaper=[[Dayton Daily News]]|date=June 21, 2018|accessdate=June 22, 2018|first=David|last=Jablonski}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mavs.com/mavericks-acquire-draft-rights-to-ray-spalding-and-kostas-antetokounmpo/|title=Mavericks acquire draft rights to Ray Spalding and Kostas Antetokounmpo|date=June 21, 2018|access-date=June 21, 2018|publisher=mavs.com}}</ref> Antetokounmpo would later sign a [[two-way contract]] on July 13. Throughout the contract, he will split his playing time between the Mavericks and their [[NBA G League]] affiliate, the [[Texas Legends]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Mavericks sign Kostas Antetokounmpo to two-way contract; waive Jalen Jones|url=https://www.mavs.com/mavericks-sign-kostas-antetokounmpo-to-two-way-contract-waive-jalen-jones/|publisher=National Basketball Association|date=July 13, 2018|accessdate=July 13, 2018}}</ref> He made his NBA debut on March 20, 2019 in a 118\u2013126 loss to the [[Portland Trail Blazers]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Lillard scores 33 points, Blazers beat Mavericks 126\u2013118|url=http://www.espn.com/nba/recap?gameId=401071746|publisher=National Basketball Association|date=March 20, 2019|accessdate=March 20, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Los Angeles Lakers / South Bay Lakers (2019\u2013present)===\nOn July 19, 2019, Antetokounmpo was waived by the Mavericks.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mavsmoneyball.com/2019/7/19/20701354/dallas-mavericks-waive-kostas-antetokounmpo=21|title=Mavericks waive Kostas Antetokounmpo|date=July 19, 2019|website=mavsmoneyball.com|access-date=July 19, 2019}}</ref> He would later be claimed by the [[Los Angeles Lakers]] on July 22, 2019.<ref>{{cite web |title=Report: Lakers claim Kostas Antetokounmpo off free agency waivers |url=https://www.nba.com/article/2019/07/21/report-lakers-claim-kostas-antetokounmpo-waivers |website=NBA |accessdate=22 July 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Lakers Awarded Kostas Antetokounmpo on Waiver Claim |url=https://www.nba.com/lakers/releases/190722-lakers-awarded-kostas-antetokounmpo-waiver-claim |website=Los Angeles Lakers |accessdate=22 July 2019}}</ref>\n\n==National team career==\nAntetokounmpo played with the junior [[Greece men's national under-20 basketball team|Greek Under-20 national team]]. He played at the [[2016 FIBA Europe Under-20 Championship Division B]], where he won a bronze medal.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://archive.fiba.com/pages/eng/fa/p/rpp//q/Ndubuisi%20ADETOKUNBO/pid/126901/_//players.html|title=archive.fiba.com: Players|website=archive.fiba.com|access-date=May 31, 2018}}</ref> During the tournament, he averaged 1.3 points, 1.8 rebounds, and 0.3 assists per game.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://archive.fiba.com/pages/eng/fa/player/p/pid/126901/sid/12474/tid/291/_/2016_FIBA_U20_European_Championship_Division_B/index.html|title=Ndubuisi Antetokounmpo profile, FIBA U20 European Championship 2016 {{!}} FIBA.COM|work=FIBA.COM|access-date=May 31, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Career statistics==\n{{NBA player statistics legend}}\n\n===NBA===\n====Regular season====\n{{NBA player statistics start}}\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| {{nbay|2018}}\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| [[2018\u201319 Dallas Mavericks season|Dallas]]\n| 2 || 0 || 5.5 || .000 || .000 || .500 || .5 || .0 || 1.0 || .0 || 1.0\n|- class=\"sortbottom\"\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" colspan=\"2\"| Career\n| 2 || 0 || 5.5 || .000 || .000 || .500 || .5 || .0 || 1.0 || .0 || 1.0\n{{S-end}}\n\n===College===\n{{NBA player statistics start}}\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| [[2017\u201318 NCAA Division I men's basketball season|2017\u201318]]\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| [[2017\u201318 Dayton Flyers men's basketball team|Dayton]]\n| 29 || 6 || 21.1 || .574 || .133 || .516 || 2.9 || .4 || .2 || 1.1 || 5.2\n{{S-end}}\n\n==Personal life==\nAntetokounmpo was born in [[Athens]], Greece, to [[Nigerians|Nigerian]] parents. He officially became a full Greek citizen in 2016.<ref>[http://www.matrix24.gr/2016/01/vgazi-elliniko-diavatirio-o-kostas-antetokounmpo/ matrix24.gr \u0392\u03b3\u03ac\u03b6\u03b5\u03b9 \u03b5\u03bb\u03bb\u03b7\u03bd\u03b9\u03ba\u03cc \u03b4\u03b9\u03b1\u03b2\u03b1\u03c4\u03ae\u03c1\u03b9\u03bf \u03bf \u039a\u03ce\u03c3\u03c4\u03b1\u03c2 \u0391\u03bd\u03c4\u03b5\u03c4\u03bf\u03ba\u03bf\u03cd\u03bd\u03bc\u03c0\u03bf {{in lang|el}}.]</ref> In addition, along with his younger sibling, Alexis, he has a Nigerian passport, which was granted to him in June 2013, so that he could gain a [[visa policy of the United States|visa]], and be allowed to legally enter into the United States.<ref>[http://www.gazzetta.gr/basketball/article/916698/i-halasmeni-kafetiera gazzetta.gr \u0397 \u03c7\u03b1\u03bb\u03b1\u03c3\u03bc\u03ad\u03bd\u03b7 \u03ba\u03b1\u03c6\u03b5\u03c4\u03b9\u03ad\u03c1\u03b1  {{in lang|el}}.]</ref>\n\nHis late father, Charles, was a former Nigerian [[association football|soccer]] player, while his mother, Veronica, was a [[high jumper]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.npr.org/2013/09/26/226268651/nbas-g-bo-wants-to-bring-hope-to-greece-and-to-milwaukee|title=NBA Rookie Wants To Bring Hope To Greece, And To Milwaukee|publisher=NPR|access-date=May 31, 2018}}</ref> Charles died in September 2017, at age 54.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/nba/recap?gameId=400974785|title=Trail Blazers vs. Bucks \u2013 Game Recap \u2013 October 21, 2017|publisher=ESPN|access-date=May 31, 2018}}</ref> His parents are from different Nigerian ethnic groups\u2014Charles was [[Yoruba people|Yoruba]], and Veronica is [[Igbo people|Igbo]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://theundefeated.com/features/bucks-giannis-antetokounmpo-greek-freak-wants-to-go-back-to-his-nigerian-roots/ |title=\u2018The Greek Freak\u2019 wants to go back to his Nigerian roots |first=Marc J. |last=Spears |publisher=[[The Undefeated (website)|The Undefeated]] |date=March 5, 2019 |accessdate=March 8, 2019}}</ref> His oldest brother, Francis, is also a professional soccer player. He is a younger brother of [[Milwaukee Bucks]] players [[Giannis Antetokounmpo|Giannis]] and [[Thanasis Antetokounmpo|Thanasis]]. He is also the older brother of Alex.<ref name=\"archdeacon\">{{cite web|last1=Archdeacon|first1=Tom|title=Flyers\u2019 Kostas Antetokounmpo tries to live up to his name|url=https://www.mydaytondailynews.com/sports/tom-archdeacon-flyers-kostas-antetokounmpo-tries-live-his-name/meHZJCKf9vQXNYVhHne5gL/|website=[[Dayton Daily News]]|accessdate=March 22, 2018|date=September 23, 2017}}</ref> As a youth, Antetokounmpo played for the junior clubs of [[Filathlitikos B.C.|Filathlitikos]], which also developed his older brothers Thanasis and Giannis.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.proballers.com/basketball/player/66983/konstantinos-antetokounmpo Proballers.com Profile]\n*[http://www.nba.com/players/kostas/antetokounmpo/1628961 NBA.com profile]\n*[http://daytonflyers.com/roster.aspx?rp_id=4218&path= Dayton Flyers bio]\n\n{{Los Angeles Lakers current roster}}\n{{South Bay Lakers current roster}}\n{{2018 NBA Draft}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Antetokounmpo, Kostas}}\n[[Category:1997 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Dallas Mavericks players]]\n[[Category:Dayton Flyers men's basketball players]]\n[[Category:Nigerian emigrants to the United States]]\n[[Category:Greek expatriate basketball people in the United States]]\n[[Category:Greek men's basketball players]]\n[[Category:Greek people of Nigerian descent]]\n[[Category:Greek people of Igbo descent]]\n[[Category:Greek people of Yoruba descent]]\n[[Category:Igbo sportspeople]]\n[[Category:Los Angeles Lakers players]]\n[[Category:Philadelphia 76ers draft picks]]\n[[Category:Power forwards (basketball)]]\n[[Category:South Bay Lakers players]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Athens]]\n[[Category:Texas Legends players]]\n[[Category:Yoruba sportspeople]]\n", "name_user": "Rockchalk717", "label": "safe", "comment": "Copy pronunciation of his last name from his brother\u2019s page", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kostas_Antetokounmpo"}
{"title_page": "Taipei World Trade Center", "text_new": "{{Expand Chinese|\u81fa\u5317\u4e16\u754c\u8cbf\u6613\u4e2d\u5fc3|date=February 2009}}\n{{Infobox building\n| name                 = Taipei World Trade Center<br>\u81fa\u5317\u4e16\u754c\u8cbf\u6613\u4e2d\u5fc3\n| native_name          = \n| former_names         =\n| alternate_names      =\n| image                = Jilong Road square of TWTC Exhibition Hall 20090617.jpg\n| alt                  = \n| caption              = Taipei World Trade Center facing [[Keelung Road|Jilong Road]]\n| map_type             = \n| map_alt              = \n| map_caption          = \n| altitude             = \n| building_type        = \n| architectural_style  = \n| structural_system    = \n| cost                 =  \n| client               = [[Taiwan External Trade Development Council]]\n| owner                = \n| current_tenants      = \n| landlord             = \n| location             = [[Xinyi District, Taipei|Xinyi]], [[Taipei]], [[Taiwan]]\n| address              = \n| coordinates          = \n| start_date           = 16 October 1982\n| completion_date      = \n| inauguration_date    = 31 December 1985\n| renovation_date      = \n| demolition_date      = \n| destruction_date     = \n| height               = \n| diameter             = \n| floor_count          = \n| floor_area           = \n| main_contractor      = \n| architect            = Haigo T. H. Shen, [[Kenzo Tange|Tange Associates]]\n| architecture_firm    =\n| structural_engineer  = \n| services_engineer    = \n| civil_engineer       = \n| awards               =\n| url                  = \n| references           =\n}}\n\nThe '''Taipei World Trade Center''' ('''TWTC'''; {{zh|t=\u81fa\u5317\u4e16\u754c\u8cbf\u6613\u4e2d\u5fc3|p=T\u00e1ib\u011bi Sh\u00ecji\u00e8 M\u00e0oy\u00ec Zh\u014dngx\u012bn}}) was inaugurated in January 1986 by [[Taiwan]]'s foremost trade promotion organization, the [[Taiwan External Trade Development Council]] (TAITRA), to provide a single, modern venue that would combine [[Trade fair|exhibition]] space, [[Conference room|conference]] facilities, [[office]]s, and [[hotel]] accommodation for [[international business]]. TWTC combines every possible service that brings together a vast consulting service on trade-related issues, trading partners, [[Distributor (business)|supplier]]s, and [[Market (economics)|markets]].\n\nThis four-in-one complex, located in the city's [[Xinyi District, Taipei|Xinyi District]], is designed to accommodate the needs of the international business community, which is why there is not just one, but four structures at the TWTC. The Exhibition Hall, [[Taipei International Convention Center|International Convention Center]], International Trade Building and [[Grand Hyatt Taipei]], all comprise one integrated business complex.\n\n==Establishment==\nThe current Taipei World Trade Center only saw completion in 1985 following many drawbacks in construction and development. However, the history of the [[Taiwan External Trade Development Council]] (TAITRA) began on 1 July 1970, where in an effort by the [[Republic of China]] Government to further develop international trade activities following accelerated economic growth in the 1970s.\n\nInitially, TAITRA did not have a specialized exhibition hall to accommodate the exhibitions of export goods. As a result of the lack of facilities, in March 1974, the [[Taipei Grand Hotel]] was chosen for the first ever [[Taipei Trade Shows]] - \"Taiwan Export Clothings Exhibition\". Subsequently, the necessity of a new exhibition hall allowed for the establishment of the TAITRA exhibition hall set up at [[Taipei Songshan Airport]]. Yet shortly afterwards due to Taiwan's rapid economic growth as one of the [[Four Asian Tigers]], TAITRA again found itself having to facilitate even larger scale exhibitions.\n\nOn 31 December 1985, the Taipei World Trade Center had its inaugural exhibition for [[IT Month]], which coincided with the opening of the Exhibition Hall. Following suit, the International Tourist Hotel (completed in 1987, renamed the [[Grand Hyatt Taipei]]), the International Trade Building (completed in 1988) and [[Taipei International Convention Center|International Convention Center]] (completed in 1989, now as TICC) were opened for use. Hence from 8 January 1990, the Taipei World Trade Center exists in its present form as an all-purpose four-in-one complex.\n\n==Main buildings==\n\n===Exhibition Building (Hall 1)===\n[[File:Computex Taipei in Taipei World Trade Center 2004-06.jpg|thumb|The exhibition hall in Taipei World Trade Center]]\n\n====Exhibition Hall====\n*First floor: Usually referred to as \"Exhibition Hall 1\". Showroom floor area is 23450 square metres, accommodates 1304 display booths, and is divided into four quadrants (A, B, C, D). Popularly, [[Taipei Trade Shows]] and other larger exhibitions are held here.\n*2nd floor: Also known as \"Area H\", has an aerial bridge that connects to [[Taipei 101]], floor area of 4789 square meters, accommodates 250 standard sized exhibition booths. Exhibitions in this area typically range from small to mid-sized local expositions or education related expositions.\n\n====Convention Room====\nLocated on the 2nd floor, divided into three rooms, mainly functions as meeting or board room for exhibition organizers, additionally, the 3rd and 4th rooms can be connected accordingly to accommodate varying delegations.\n\n====TAITRA Book Store====\n[[File:TAITRA Book Store.jpg|thumb|TAITRA Book Store]]\nOpen for business during weekdays, or on holidays when there is an exhibition. Book collection mainly comprises sales trading-related items. When [[Taipei Trade Shows]] are going on at the time, it also provides exhibitor directory lists.\n\n====Trade Market (sales display)====\nCatering to different needs, the 2nd to 6th floors are set as an \"Export Market\", with the 7th floor as the \"Import Market\".  First opened in June 1985 for product export companies to register for sales. There are currently 1052 displays.\n\n===Exhibition Hall 3===\nStart to use from 18 September 2003, showground area is 7481 square meter, able to accommodate 365 display booths, and floors above 2nd floor are planned into parking area. During large exhibition periods, the parking rate will adjust accordingly.\n\n==Important exhibitions==\n[[File:2007AutoTronicsTaipei Day4-21.jpg|thumb|Taipei Trade Shows - AutoTronics Taipei]]\n*[[Taipei International Book Exhibition]] \n*[[COMPUTEX]] \n*[[Taipei Computer Application Show]] \n*[[IT Month]] <ref>[http://www.itmonth.org.tw/ IT Month]</ref>\n*[[Taipei International Travel Fair]] <ref>[http://www.taipeiitf.org.tw/ Taipei International Travel Fair]</ref>\n*[[Taiwan External Trade Development Council|TAITRA]] [[Taiwan Trade Shows]]\n\n==Access==\nThe building is accessible from [[Taipei 101 / World Trade Center Station]] of the [[Taipei Metro]].\n\n==See also==\n* [[Taipei Nangang Exhibition Center]]\n* [[Taipei 101/World Trade Center Station]]\n* [[Grand Hyatt Taipei]]\n* [[World Trade Center Taichung]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Taipei World Trade Center}}\n{{Wikinewscat|Taipei World Trade Center}}\n* {{facebook|\u81fa\u5317\u4e16\u754c\u8cbf\u6613\u4e2d\u5fc3-318898531459466}}\n*[http://www.taiwantrade.com.tw/ TAIWANTRADE]\n*[http://www.twtc.org.tw/ Taipei World Trade Center]\n*[http://www.twtcmart.com.tw/ Taipei World Trade Center Export and Import Mart]\n*[http://www.emporis.com/building/internationaltradebuilding-taipei-taiwan]\n\n{{Coord|25|2|2|N|121|33|44|E|region:ID_type:landmark|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:1985 establishments in Taiwan]]\n[[Category:Infrastructure completed in 1985]]\n[[Category:Convention centers in Taipei]]\n[[Category:Tourist attractions in Taipei]]\n[[Category:Economy of Taipei]]\n[[Category:World Trade Centers]]\n[[Category:Xinyi Special District]]\n", "text_old": "{{Expand Chinese|\u81fa\u5317\u4e16\u754c\u8cbf\u6613\u4e2d\u5fc3|date=February 2009}}\n{{Infobox building\n| name                 = Taipei World Trade Center<br>\u81fa\u5317\u4e16\u754c\u8cbf\u6613\u4e2d\u5fc3\n| native_name          = \n| former_names         =\n| alternate_names      =\n| image                = Jilong Road square of TWTC Exhibition Hall 20090617.jpg\n| alt                  = \n| caption              = Taipei World Trade Center facing [[Keelung Road|Jilong Road]]\n| map_type             = \n| map_alt              = \n| map_caption          = \n| altitude             = \n| building_type        = \n| architectural_style  = \n| structural_system    = \n| cost                 =  \n| client               = [[Taiwan External Trade Development Council]]\n| owner                = \n| current_tenants      = \n| landlord             = \n| location             = [[Xinyi District, Taipei|Xinyi]], [[Taipei]], [[Taiwan]]\n| address              = \n| coordinates          = \n| start_date           = 16 October 1982\n| completion_date      = \n| inauguration_date    = 31 December 1985\n| renovation_date      = \n| demolition_date      = \n| destruction_date     = \n| height               = \n| diameter             = \n| floor_count          = \n| floor_area           = \n| main_contractor      = \n| architect            = Haigo T. H. Shen, [[Kenzo Tange|Tange Associates]]\n| architecture_firm    =\n| structural_engineer  = \n| services_engineer    = \n| civil_engineer       = \n| awards               =\n| url                  = \n| references           =\n}}\n\nThe '''Taipei World Trade Center''' ('''TWTC'''; {{zh|t=\u81fa\u5317\u4e16\u754c\u8cbf\u6613\u4e2d\u5fc3|p=T\u00e1ib\u011bi Sh\u00ecji\u00e8 M\u00e0oy\u00ec Zh\u014dngx\u012bn}}) was inagurated in January 1986 by [[Taiwan]]'s foremost trade promotion organization, the [[Taiwan External Trade Development Council]] (TAITRA), to provide a single, modern venue that would combine [[Trade fair|exhibition]] space, [[Conference room|conference]] facilities, [[office]]s, and [[hotel]] accommodation for [[international business]]. TWTC combines every possible service that brings together a vast consulting service on trade-related issues, trading partners, [[Distributor (business)|supplier]]s, and [[Market (economics)|markets]].\n\nThis four-in-one complex, located in the city's [[Xinyi District, Taipei|Xinyi District]], is designed to accommodate the needs of the international business community, which is why there is not just one, but four structures at the TWTC. The Exhibition Hall, [[Taipei International Convention Center|International Convention Center]], International Trade Building and [[Grand Hyatt Taipei]], all comprise one integrated business complex.\n\n==Establishment==\nThe current Taipei World Trade Center only saw completion in 1985 following many drawbacks in construction and development. However, the history of the [[Taiwan External Trade Development Council]] (TAITRA) began on 1 July 1970, where in an effort by the [[Republic of China]] Government to further develop international trade activities following accelerated economic growth in the 1970s.\n\nInitially, TAITRA did not have a specialized exhibition hall to accommodate the exhibitions of export goods. As a result of the lack of facilities, in March 1974, the [[Taipei Grand Hotel]] was chosen for the first ever [[Taipei Trade Shows]] - \"Taiwan Export Clothings Exhibition\". Subsequently, the necessity of a new exhibition hall allowed for the establishment of the TAITRA exhibition hall set up at [[Taipei Songshan Airport]]. Yet shortly afterwards due to Taiwan's rapid economic growth as one of the [[Four Asian Tigers]], TAITRA again found itself having to facilitate even larger scale exhibitions.\n\nOn 31 December 1985, the Taipei World Trade Center had its inaugural exhibition for [[IT Month]], which coincided with the opening of the Exhibition Hall. Following suit, the International Tourist Hotel (completed in 1987, renamed the [[Grand Hyatt Taipei]]), the International Trade Building (completed in 1988) and [[Taipei International Convention Center|International Convention Center]] (completed in 1989, now as TICC) were opened for use. Hence from 8 January 1990, the Taipei World Trade Center exists in its present form as an all-purpose four-in-one complex.\n\n==Main buildings==\n\n===Exhibition Building (Hall 1)===\n[[File:Computex Taipei in Taipei World Trade Center 2004-06.jpg|thumb|The exhibition hall in Taipei World Trade Center]]\n\n====Exhibition Hall====\n*First floor: Usually referred to as \"Exhibition Hall 1\". Showroom floor area is 23450 square metres, accommodates 1304 display booths, and is divided into four quadrants (A, B, C, D). Popularly, [[Taipei Trade Shows]] and other larger exhibitions are held here.\n*2nd floor: Also known as \"Area H\", has an aerial bridge that connects to [[Taipei 101]], floor area of 4789 square meters, accommodates 250 standard sized exhibition booths. Exhibitions in this area typically range from small to mid-sized local expositions or education related expositions.\n\n====Convention Room====\nLocated on the 2nd floor, divided into three rooms, mainly functions as meeting or board room for exhibition organizers, additionally, the 3rd and 4th rooms can be connected accordingly to accommodate varying delegations.\n\n====TAITRA Book Store====\n[[File:TAITRA Book Store.jpg|thumb|TAITRA Book Store]]\nOpen for business during weekdays, or on holidays when there is an exhibition. Book collection mainly comprises sales trading-related items. When [[Taipei Trade Shows]] are going on at the time, it also provides exhibitor directory lists.\n\n====Trade Market (sales display)====\nCatering to different needs, the 2nd to 6th floors are set as an \"Export Market\", with the 7th floor as the \"Import Market\".  First opened in June 1985 for product export companies to register for sales. There are currently 1052 displays.\n\n===Exhibition Hall 3===\nStart to use from 18 September 2003, showground area is 7481 square meter, able to accommodate 365 display booths, and floors above 2nd floor are planned into parking area. During large exhibition periods, the parking rate will adjust accordingly.\n\n==Important exhibitions==\n[[File:2007AutoTronicsTaipei Day4-21.jpg|thumb|Taipei Trade Shows - AutoTronics Taipei]]\n*[[Taipei International Book Exhibition]] \n*[[COMPUTEX]] \n*[[Taipei Computer Application Show]] \n*[[IT Month]] <ref>[http://www.itmonth.org.tw/ IT Month]</ref>\n*[[Taipei International Travel Fair]] <ref>[http://www.taipeiitf.org.tw/ Taipei International Travel Fair]</ref>\n*[[Taiwan External Trade Development Council|TAITRA]] [[Taiwan Trade Shows]]\n\n==Access==\nThe building is accessible from [[Taipei 101 / World Trade Center Station]] of the [[Taipei Metro]].\n\n==See also==\n* [[Taipei Nangang Exhibition Center]]\n* [[Taipei 101/World Trade Center Station]]\n* [[Grand Hyatt Taipei]]\n* [[World Trade Center Taichung]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Taipei World Trade Center}}\n{{Wikinewscat|Taipei World Trade Center}}\n* {{facebook|\u81fa\u5317\u4e16\u754c\u8cbf\u6613\u4e2d\u5fc3-318898531459466}}\n*[http://www.taiwantrade.com.tw/ TAIWANTRADE]\n*[http://www.twtc.org.tw/ Taipei World Trade Center]\n*[http://www.twtcmart.com.tw/ Taipei World Trade Center Export and Import Mart]\n*[http://www.emporis.com/building/internationaltradebuilding-taipei-taiwan]\n\n{{Coord|25|2|2|N|121|33|44|E|region:ID_type:landmark|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:1985 establishments in Taiwan]]\n[[Category:Infrastructure completed in 1985]]\n[[Category:Convention centers in Taipei]]\n[[Category:Tourist attractions in Taipei]]\n[[Category:Economy of Taipei]]\n[[Category:World Trade Centers]]\n[[Category:Xinyi Special District]]\n", "name_user": "Daknalo", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fix typo", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Taipei_World_Trade_Center"}
{"title_page": "David Bashevkin", "text_new": "{{short description|American rabbi and professor}}\n{{Infobox Jewish leader\n|honorific-prefix =Rabbi\n|name        = David Bashevkin\n|honorific-suffix = \n|title       = \n|image       = \n|caption     = \n|denomination=[[Orthodox Judaism]]\n|synagogue   =\n|synagogueposition =\n|yeshiva     = \n|yeshivaposition  =\n|organization= [[NCSY]]\n|organisationposition = Director of Education\n|began       = \n|ended       = \n|predecessor = \n|successor   = \n|semicha     = \n|rabbi       = \n|rank        = \n|other_post  = \n|birth_name  = \n|birth_date  = \n|birth_place = \n|death_date  = \n|death_place = \n|buried      = \n|nationality = American\n|residence   = [[Teaneck, New Jersey]]\n|parents     = \n|spouse      = \n|children    = \n|occupation  = Rabbi, professor, writer\n|profession  = \n|employer    = \n|education   = [[Yeshiva University]]\n|alma_mater  = [[The New School]] ([[Milano School of International Affairs, Management, and Urban Policy]])\n|signature   = \n|website     = \n}}\n'''David Bashevkin''' (also spelled '''Dovid Bashevkin''') is an American Jewish rabbi, writer, and professor based in New York. He is currently Director of Education of [[NCSY]], an [[Orthodox Union]] youth group.<ref>[https://ncsy.org/staff/ NCSY staff page].</ref><ref name=\"mishpacha\">{{cite web |url=https://mishpacha.com/contributors/rabbi-dovid-bashevkin/ |title=Dovid Bashevkin |last= |first= |date= |publisher=Mishpacha Jewish Family Weekly |access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\nBashevkin earned his Bachelor's degree in [[Talmud]]ic Studies at [[Ner Israel Rabbinical College]] in 2006. After receiving his rabbinic ordination at [[Yeshiva University]], he graduated with a Master of Arts (MA) degree in Jewish/Judaic studies under [[Yaakov Elman]] at [[Yeshiva University]] in 2010. From 2013 to 2017, he studied for a Ph.D. in Public Policy Analysis at [[The New School]]'s [[Milano School of International Affairs, Management, and Urban Policy]], where he focused on crisis management.<ref name=\"myjewishlearning\">{{cite web |url=https://www.myjewishlearning.com/eli-talks/why-are-you-here-truth-comfort-and-religious-motivation/ |title=Why are You Here? Truth, Comfort, and Religious Motivation |last=Bashevkin |first=Dovid |date= |publisher=My Jewish Learning |access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nBashevkin is the current director of education at the [[NCSY]] Jewish youth group, a division of the [[Orthodox Union]]. As the leader of NCSY, he has directed many youth seminars and programs, and has also developed curriculum for staff and teens<ref>{{cite web |url=https://staff.ncsy.org/education/ |title=NCSY education |last= |first= |date= |publisher=NCSY |access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref>\n\nBashevkin began his academic career as an associate director of education at [[NCSY]] from 2010 to 2013, and became the director in 2013. He has also served as an adjunct professor at [[Long Island University]] from 2010 to 2011.<ref name=\"mishpacha\"/><ref name=\"myjewishlearning\"/> He currently teaches at [[Yeshiva University]] in the Isaac Breuer College of Hebraic Studies,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.yu.edu/torah-studies/ibc/staff |title=Undergraduate Torah Studies: Isaac Breuer College of Hebraic Studies (IBC) |last= |first= |date= |publisher=Yeshiva University |access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref> as well as in the [[Sy Syms School of Business]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://edublog.news/2019/05/10/celebration-of-university-authors/ |title=Celebration of University Authors |last= |first= |date=2019-05-10 |publisher=Edublog |access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref>\n\nHe is the Talmud study partner of [[Liel Leibovitz]], where they developed a ''[[Tablet (magazine)|Tablet]]'' [[Daf Yomi]] podcast called ''Take One''<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.tabletmag.com/podcasts/take-one |title=Take One |last= |first= |date= |publisher=Tablet Magazine |access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.tabletmag.com/sections/news/articles/arguing-about-the-talmud |title=Arguing About the Talmud |last= |first= |date=March 8, 2020 |publisher=Tablet Magazine |access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref> Bashevkin is a writer for ''[[Mishpacha]]'' magazine as well, where he has written a humor column called \u201cTop 5\u201d, cataloguing the idiosyncrasies and nuances of Jewish life.<ref name=\"mishpacha\"/>\n\n==Publications==\n===Books===\nBashevkin's published books include ''B'Rogez Rachem Tizkor''<ref>[https://www.hebrewbooks.org/53838 B'Rogez Rachem Tizkor].</ref><ref>Bashevkin, Dovid. [http://www.thelehrhaus.com/timely-thoughts/2016/9/29/jonah-and-the-varieties-of-religious-motivation-a-religious-educators-perspective-on-why-people-become-religious \"Jonah and the Varieties of Religious Motivation.\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161012155807/http://www.thelehrhaus.com/timely-thoughts/2016/9/29/jonah-and-the-varieties-of-religious-motivation-a-religious-educators-perspective-on-why-people-become-religious# |date=2016-10-12 }} ''Lehrhaus''. 9 October 2016. 2 October 2017.</ref> and ''Sin\u2022a\u2022gogue: Sin and Failure in Jewish Thoughts''.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.jpost.com/opinion/book-review-growing-through-sin-595233 |title=Book review: Growing through sin? |last=Rosenbaum |first=Alan |date=July 10, 2019 |publisher=The Jerusalem Post |access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref><ref name=\"timesofisrael\"/>\n\n''Sin\u2022a\u2022gogue'' draws extensively from the works of Rabbi [[Zadok HaKohen]] Rabinowitz, a 19th-century Chasidic rabbi.<ref name=\"timesofisrael\">{{cite web |url=https://jewishstandard.timesofisrael.com/sin-failure-and-the-haggadah/ |title=Sin, failure, and the Haggadah |last=Yudelson |first=Larry |date=April 11, 2019 |publisher=Times of Israel |access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref> Many of Bashevkin's ideas in the book were based on Zadok's theology on [[sin]].\n\nHe also authored the [[NCSY]] [[Haggadah]] entitled ''Just One''.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://menuchapublishers.com/products/just-one-the-ncsy-haggadah |title=Just One - The NCSY Haggadah |last=Bashevkin |first=Dovid |date=Jan 27, 2019 |publisher=Menucha Publishers |access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref>\n\n===Articles===\nBashevkin has written various articles on [[Jewish theology]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.tabletmag.com/contributors/dovid-bashevkin |title=Dovid Bashevkin |last= |first= |date= |publisher=Tablet Magazine |access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref> He has published many other articles on [[sin]], failure,<ref>Silver, Jonathan, host.  [https://tikvahfund.org/library/podcast-david-bashevkin-on-sin-and-failure-in-jewish-thought/ \"Podcast: David Bashevkin on Sin and Failure in Jewish Thought.\"] ''The Tikvah Podcast'', The Tikvah Fund, 3 Oct. 2019.</ref> and Jewish doctrine and tradition, including the application of [[Jewish scripture]] in the 21st-century digital age.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.academia.edu/28247291/David_Bashevkin_Medium_Matters_The_Medium_and_Message_of_Torah_in_the_Digital_Age_Shavuot-To-Go_2016_6-9 |title=Bashevkin, David. \"Medium Matters: The Medium and Message of Torah in the Digital Age,\" Shavuot-To-Go (2016): 6-9 |last= |first= |date= |publisher= |access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.firstthings.com/web-exclusives/2014/05/life-is-full-of-failure-bio-blurbs-should-be-too |title=Life Is Full of Failure. Bio Blurbs Should Be Too. |last=Bashevkin |first=David |date=2014-05-08 |publisher=First Things |access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref>\n\nSome of his published articles are:\n*\"[https://www.academia.edu/41047286/David_Bashevkin_MeToo_Should_Include_SinToo_Wall_Street_Journal_3_October_2019_ #MeToo Should Include #SinToo],\" ''Wall Street Journal'' (3 October 2019).\n*\"[https://www.academia.edu/38664661/David_Bashevkin_Failure_Comes_To_Yeshivah_Jewish_Action_Spring_2019_62-64 Failure Comes To Yeshivah],\" ''Jewish Action'' (Spring 2019): 62-64.\n*\"[https://www.academia.edu/33792997/David_Bashevkin_Rabbi_s_Son_Syndrome_Religious_Struggle_in_a_World_of_Religious_Ideals_Jewish_Action_Summer_2017_38-44 Rabbi\u2019s Son Syndrome: Religious Struggle in a World of Religious Ideals],\" ''Jewish Action'' (Summer 2017): 38-44.\n*\"[https://www.academia.edu/30430104/David_Bashevkin_Jonah_and_the_Varieties_of_Religious_Motivation_The_Lehrhaus_9_October_2016_ Jonah and the Varieties of Religious Motivation],\" ''The Lehrhaus'' (9 October 2016).\n*\"[https://www.academia.edu/30430043/David_Bashevkin_Letters_of_Love_and_Rebuke_From_Rav_Yitzchok_Hutner_Tablet_Magazine_10_October_2016_ Letters of Love and Rebuke From Rav Yitzchok Hutner],\" ''Tablet Magazine'' (10 October 2016).\n*\"[https://www.academia.edu/28247291/David_Bashevkin_Medium_Matters_The_Medium_and_Message_of_Torah_in_the_Digital_Age_Shavuot-To-Go_2016_6-9 Medium Matters: The Medium and Message of Torah in the Digital Age],\" ''Shavuot-To-Go'' (2016): 6-9.\n*\"[https://www.academia.edu/28247025/David_Bashevkin_A_Radical_Theology_and_a_Traditional_Community_On_the_Contemporary_Application_of_Izbica_Lublin_Hasidut_in_the_Jewish_Community_TorahMusings.com_August_2015_54-68 A Radical Theology and a Traditional Community: On the Contemporary Application of Izbica\u2013Lublin Hasidut in the Jewish Community],\" ''TorahMusings.com'' (August 2015): 54-68.\n*\"[https://www.academia.edu/28247504/David_Bashevkin_The_Forgotten_Talmud_On_Teaching_Aggadah_in_High_Schools_Jewish_Action_Fall_2015_ The Forgotten Talmud: On Teaching Aggadah in High Schools],\" ''Jewish Action'' (Fall 2015).\n*\"[https://www.academia.edu/28247454/David_Bashevkin_Life_is_Full_of_Failure_Bio_Blurbs_Should_Be_Too_First_Things_8_May_2014_ Life is Full of Failure: Bio Blurbs Should Be Too],\" ''First Things'' (8 May 2014).\n*\"[https://www.academia.edu/28247169/David_Bashevkin_The_Custom_to_Recite_the_Priestly_Blessings_After_Birkat_ha-Torah_ha-Maor_68_1_2015_86-90_Hebrew_ The Custom to Recite the Priestly Blessings After Birkat ha-Torah],\" ''ha-Maor'' 68:1 (2015): 86-90 (in Hebrew).\n*\"[https://www.academia.edu/28247554/David_Bashevkin_The_Pew_Report_s_Lesser-Known_Cousin_The_Phew_Report_Jewish_Action_Summer_2014_ The Pew Report\u2019s Lesser-Known Cousin: The Phew Report],\" ''Jewish Action'' (Summer 2014).\n*\"[https://www.academia.edu/28247624/David_Bashevkin_The_Jewish_Community_Confronts_Its_Crisis_Crisis_Jewish_Action_Summer_2013_ The Jewish Community Confronts Its Crisis Crisis],\" ''Jewish Action'' (Summer 2013).\n*\"[https://www.academia.edu/28325627/David_Bashevkin_Perpetual_Prophecy_An_Intellectual_Tribute_to_Reb_Zadok_ha-Kohen_of_Lublin_on_his_110th_Yahrzeit_the_Seforim_blog_19_August_2010_ Perpetual Prophecy: An Intellectual Tribute to Reb Zadok ha-Kohen of Lublin on his 110th Yahrzeit],\" ''Seforim'' (19 August 2010).\n\n==See also==\n*[[Yaakov Elman]]\n*[[Zadok HaKohen]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.yutorah.org/rabbi-dovid-bashevkin/ Articles and lectures] on YUTorah\n*[https://yeshiva.academia.edu/DavidBashevkin Academia.edu page]\n*[https://mishpacha.com/contributors/rabbi-dovid-bashevkin/ Mishpacha articles]\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bashevkin, David}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American Jews]]\n[[Category:American rabbis]]\n[[Category:Yeshiva University alumni]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American rabbi and professor}}\n{{Infobox Jewish leader\n|honorific-prefix =Rabbi\n|name        = David Bashevkin\n|honorific-suffix = \n|title       = \n|image       = \n|caption     = \n|denomination=[[Orthodox Judaism]]\n|synagogue   =\n|synagogueposition =\n|yeshiva     = \n|yeshivaposition  =\n|organization= [[NCSY]]\n|organisationposition = Director of Education\n|began       = \n|ended       = \n|predecessor = \n|successor   = \n|semicha     = \n|rabbi       = \n|rank        = \n|other_post  = \n|birth_name  = \n|birth_date  = \n|birth_place = \n|death_date  = \n|death_place = \n|buried      = \n|nationality = American\n|residence   = [[Teaneck, New Jersey]]\n|parents     = \n|spouse      = \n|children    = \n|occupation  = Rabbi, professor, writer\n|profession  = \n|employer    = \n|education   = [[Yeshiva University]]\n|alma_mater  = [[The New School]] ([[Milano School of International Affairs, Management, and Urban Policy]])\n|signature   = \n|website     = \n}}\n'''David Bashevkin''' (also spelled '''Dovid Bashevkin''') is an American Jewish rabbi, writer, and professor based in New York. He is currently Director of Education of [[NCSY]], an [[Orthodox Union]] youth group.<ref name=\"mishpacha\">{{cite web |url=https://mishpacha.com/contributors/rabbi-dovid-bashevkin/ |title=Dovid Bashevkin |last= |first= |date= |publisher=Mishpacha Jewish Family Weekly |access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\nBashevkin earned his Bachelor's degree in [[Talmud]]ic Studies at [[Ner Israel Rabbinical College]] in 2006. After receiving his rabbinic ordination at [[Yeshiva University]], he graduated with a Master of Arts (MA) degree in Jewish/Judaic studies under [[Yaakov Elman]] at [[Yeshiva University]] in 2010. From 2013 to 2017, he studied for a Ph.D. in Public Policy Analysis at [[The New School]]'s [[Milano School of International Affairs, Management, and Urban Policy]], where he focused on crisis management.<ref name=\"myjewishlearning\">{{cite web |url=https://www.myjewishlearning.com/eli-talks/why-are-you-here-truth-comfort-and-religious-motivation/ |title=Why are You Here? Truth, Comfort, and Religious Motivation |last=Bashevkin |first=Dovid |date= |publisher=My Jewish Learning |access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nBashevkin is the current director of education at the [[NCSY]] Jewish youth group, a division of the [[Orthodox Union]]. As the leader of NCSY, he has directed many youth seminars and programs, and has also developed curriculum for staff and teens<ref>{{cite web |url=https://staff.ncsy.org/education/ |title=NCSY education |last= |first= |date= |publisher=NCSY |access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref>\n\nBashevkin began his academic career as an associate director of education at [[NCSY]] from 2010 to 2013, and became the director in 2013. He has also served as an adjunct professor at [[Long Island University]] from 2010 to 2011.<ref name=\"mishpacha\"/><ref name=\"myjewishlearning\"/> He currently teaches at [[Yeshiva University]] in the Isaac Breuer College of Hebraic Studies,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.yu.edu/torah-studies/ibc/staff |title=Undergraduate Torah Studies: Isaac Breuer College of Hebraic Studies (IBC) |last= |first= |date= |publisher=Yeshiva University |access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref> as well as in the [[Sy Syms School of Business]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://edublog.news/2019/05/10/celebration-of-university-authors/ |title=Celebration of University Authors |last= |first= |date=2019-05-10 |publisher=Edublog |access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref>\n\nHe is the Talmud study partner of [[Liel Leibovitz]], where they developed a Tablet Daf Yomi podcast called ''Take One''<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.tabletmag.com/podcasts/take-one |title=Take One |last= |first= |date= |publisher=Tablet Magazine |access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.tabletmag.com/sections/news/articles/arguing-about-the-talmud |title=Arguing About the Talmud |last= |first= |date=March 8, 2020 |publisher=Tablet Magazine |access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref> Bashevkin is a writer for Mishpacha magazine as well, where he has written a humor column called \u201cTop 5\u201d, cataloguing the idiosyncrasies and nuances of Jewish life.<ref name=\"mishpacha\"/>\n\n==Publications==\n===Books===\nBashevkin's published books include ''B'Rogez Rachem Tizkor''<ref>Bashevkin, Dovid. [http://www.thelehrhaus.com/timely-thoughts/2016/9/29/jonah-and-the-varieties-of-religious-motivation-a-religious-educators-perspective-on-why-people-become-religious \"Jonah and the Varieties of Religious Motivation.\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161012155807/http://www.thelehrhaus.com/timely-thoughts/2016/9/29/jonah-and-the-varieties-of-religious-motivation-a-religious-educators-perspective-on-why-people-become-religious# |date=2016-10-12 }} ''Lehrhaus''. 9 October 2016. 2 October 2017.</ref> and ''Sin\u2022a\u2022gogue: Sin and Failure in Jewish Thoughts''.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.jpost.com/opinion/book-review-growing-through-sin-595233 |title=Book review: Growing through sin? |last=Rosenbaum |first=Alan |date=July 10, 2019 |publisher=The Jerusalem Post |access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref><ref name=\"timesofisrael\"/>\n\n''Sin\u2022a\u2022gogue'' draws extensively from the works of Rabbi [[Zadok HaKohen]] Rabinowitz, a 19th-century Chasidic rabbi.<ref name=\"timesofisrael\">{{cite web |url=https://jewishstandard.timesofisrael.com/sin-failure-and-the-haggadah/ |title=Sin, failure, and the Haggadah |last=Yudelson |first=Larry |date=April 11, 2019 |publisher=Times of Israel |access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref> Many of Bashevkin's ideas in the book were based on Zadok's theology on [[sin]].\n\nHe also authored the [[NCSY]] [[Haggadah]] entitled ''Just One''.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://menuchapublishers.com/products/just-one-the-ncsy-haggadah |title=Just One - The NCSY Haggadah |last=Bashevkin |first=Dovid |date=Jan 27, 2019 |publisher=Menucha Publishers |access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref>\n\n===Articles===\nBashevkin has written various articles on [[Jewish theology]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.tabletmag.com/contributors/dovid-bashevkin |title=Dovid Bashevkin |last= |first= |date= |publisher=Tablet Magazine |access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref> He has published many other articles on [[sin]], failure,<ref>Silver, Jonathan, host.  [https://tikvahfund.org/library/podcast-david-bashevkin-on-sin-and-failure-in-jewish-thought/ \"Podcast: David Bashevkin on Sin and Failure in Jewish Thought.\"] ''The Tikvah Podcast'', The Tikvah Fund, 3 Oct. 2019.</ref> and Jewish doctrine and tradition, including the application of [[Jewish scripture]] in the 21st-century digital age.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.academia.edu/28247291/David_Bashevkin_Medium_Matters_The_Medium_and_Message_of_Torah_in_the_Digital_Age_Shavuot-To-Go_2016_6-9 |title=Bashevkin, David. \"Medium Matters: The Medium and Message of Torah in the Digital Age,\" Shavuot-To-Go (2016): 6-9 |last= |first= |date= |publisher= |access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.firstthings.com/web-exclusives/2014/05/life-is-full-of-failure-bio-blurbs-should-be-too |title=Life Is Full of Failure. Bio Blurbs Should Be Too. |last=Bashevkin |first=David |date=2014-05-08 |publisher=First Things |access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref>\n\nSome of his published articles are:\n*\"[https://www.academia.edu/41047286/David_Bashevkin_MeToo_Should_Include_SinToo_Wall_Street_Journal_3_October_2019_ #MeToo Should Include #SinToo],\" ''Wall Street Journal'' (3 October 2019).\n*\"[https://www.academia.edu/38664661/David_Bashevkin_Failure_Comes_To_Yeshivah_Jewish_Action_Spring_2019_62-64 Failure Comes To Yeshivah],\" ''Jewish Action'' (Spring 2019): 62-64.\n*\"[https://www.academia.edu/33792997/David_Bashevkin_Rabbi_s_Son_Syndrome_Religious_Struggle_in_a_World_of_Religious_Ideals_Jewish_Action_Summer_2017_38-44 Rabbi\u2019s Son Syndrome: Religious Struggle in a World of Religious Ideals],\" ''Jewish Action'' (Summer 2017): 38-44.\n*\"[https://www.academia.edu/30430104/David_Bashevkin_Jonah_and_the_Varieties_of_Religious_Motivation_The_Lehrhaus_9_October_2016_ Jonah and the Varieties of Religious Motivation],\" ''The Lehrhaus'' (9 October 2016).\n*\"[https://www.academia.edu/30430043/David_Bashevkin_Letters_of_Love_and_Rebuke_From_Rav_Yitzchok_Hutner_Tablet_Magazine_10_October_2016_ Letters of Love and Rebuke From Rav Yitzchok Hutner],\" ''Tablet Magazine'' (10 October 2016).\n*\"[https://www.academia.edu/28247291/David_Bashevkin_Medium_Matters_The_Medium_and_Message_of_Torah_in_the_Digital_Age_Shavuot-To-Go_2016_6-9 Medium Matters: The Medium and Message of Torah in the Digital Age],\" ''Shavuot-To-Go'' (2016): 6-9.\n*\"[https://www.academia.edu/28247025/David_Bashevkin_A_Radical_Theology_and_a_Traditional_Community_On_the_Contemporary_Application_of_Izbica_Lublin_Hasidut_in_the_Jewish_Community_TorahMusings.com_August_2015_54-68 A Radical Theology and a Traditional Community: On the Contemporary Application of Izbica\u2013Lublin Hasidut in the Jewish Community],\" ''TorahMusings.com'' (August 2015): 54-68.\n*\"[https://www.academia.edu/28247504/David_Bashevkin_The_Forgotten_Talmud_On_Teaching_Aggadah_in_High_Schools_Jewish_Action_Fall_2015_ The Forgotten Talmud: On Teaching Aggadah in High Schools],\" ''Jewish Action'' (Fall 2015).\n*\"[https://www.academia.edu/28247454/David_Bashevkin_Life_is_Full_of_Failure_Bio_Blurbs_Should_Be_Too_First_Things_8_May_2014_ Life is Full of Failure: Bio Blurbs Should Be Too],\" ''First Things'' (8 May 2014).\n*\"[https://www.academia.edu/28247169/David_Bashevkin_The_Custom_to_Recite_the_Priestly_Blessings_After_Birkat_ha-Torah_ha-Maor_68_1_2015_86-90_Hebrew_ The Custom to Recite the Priestly Blessings After Birkat ha-Torah],\" ''ha-Maor'' 68:1 (2015): 86-90 (in Hebrew).\n*\"[https://www.academia.edu/28247554/David_Bashevkin_The_Pew_Report_s_Lesser-Known_Cousin_The_Phew_Report_Jewish_Action_Summer_2014_ The Pew Report\u2019s Lesser-Known Cousin: The Phew Report],\" ''Jewish Action'' (Summer 2014).\n*\"[https://www.academia.edu/28247624/David_Bashevkin_The_Jewish_Community_Confronts_Its_Crisis_Crisis_Jewish_Action_Summer_2013_ The Jewish Community Confronts Its Crisis Crisis],\" ''Jewish Action'' (Summer 2013).\n*\"[https://www.academia.edu/28325627/David_Bashevkin_Perpetual_Prophecy_An_Intellectual_Tribute_to_Reb_Zadok_ha-Kohen_of_Lublin_on_his_110th_Yahrzeit_the_Seforim_blog_19_August_2010_ Perpetual Prophecy: An Intellectual Tribute to Reb Zadok ha-Kohen of Lublin on his 110th Yahrzeit],\" ''Seforim'' (19 August 2010).\n\n==See also==\